## Recurring conflicts: record once, replay forever (`rerere`)

Because CI rebases `distro/nix` and `main` onto upstream every six hours, the few
files this fork rewrites conflict against upstream the **same way every cycle**.
`git rerere` ("reuse recorded resolution") records how you resolved a conflict
hunk and replays it automatically the next time the same hunk reappears, so each
recurring conflict is resolved *once, ever*.

rerere's recordings normally live in `$GIT_DIR/rr-cache`, which is per-clone and
never pushed, so CI would start empty and re-fail every cycle. To fix that, the
recordings are shared through a **tracked `.rerere-cache/` directory**:

- Every clone enables rerere and imports the shared recordings automatically on
  dev-shell entry (`scripts/rerere-cache.sh setup`, run from the flake
  `shellHook`). `scripts/sync-local.sh` does the same before its rebases.
- When a `sync-local.sh` rebase hits a **new** recurring conflict, resolve it
  once, then capture and commit the recording:

  ```sh
  scripts/rerere-cache.sh export
  git add .rerere-cache && git commit -m "fork: record rerere resolution"
  ```

- CI (`nix.yml` `sync-upstream`) imports `.rerere-cache` and rebases through
  `scripts/rerere-rebase.sh`, which auto-continues on recognised conflicts and
  **fails the job loudly on a genuinely new conflict** so a human resolves it
  once. `.rerere-cache/` is outside the Nix build `src` fileset, so committing
  resolutions never triggers a rebuild.

`scripts/rerere-cache.sh status` shows the tracked/live counts and whether rerere
is enabled in the current clone.

## Staying in sync without thinking about it

`scripts/fork-nudge.sh` is a fast, non-blocking drift reminder so the local clone
never silently lags the 6h-rebased rails. The devShell `shellHook` runs it on
entry (direnv fires it on `cd`), so just being in the repo nudges you.

It is compute-frugal and idiot-proof by design:

- It reads **already-fetched** remote-tracking refs for an instant verdict and
  never blocks shell entry on the network.
- When those cached refs are older than `FORK_NUDGE_MAX_AGE` (default 3h) it kicks
  a **background** `git fetch` so the next entry is accurate.
- It **auto fast-forwards `main` only in the unambiguously safe case**: strictly
  behind, clean working tree, on `main`, zero local-only commits. Anything that
  would need a rebase is a printed nudge to run `scripts/sync-local.sh`, never a
  surprise rebase.

Knobs: `FORK_NUDGE_DISABLE=1` (off), `FORK_NUDGE_AUTOSYNC=0` (nudge only, never
auto-ff), `FORK_NUDGE_QUIET=1` (silent when in sync), `FORK_NUDGE_MAX_AGE=<secs>`.


Policy per rail:

- `vendor/upstream`: hard-reset to `github/vendor/upstream` (mirror; aborts loud
  if it somehow carries local-only commits).
- `distro/nix`, `main`: reset when the local branch is strictly behind, otherwise
  rebase local commits onto the GitHub tip. A rebase conflict aborts cleanly and
  leaves the branch untouched.

After syncing `main`, bump the consumer pin (see below).

## End-to-end maintenance loop

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  U["upstream/master<br/>1jehuang/jcode"] -->|"6h scheduler<br/>(fork-maintenance.yml)"| CI
  CI["nix.yml sync-upstream:<br/>ff vendor/upstream,<br/>rebase distro/nix, then main<br/>(force-with-lease)"] --> GH["github/jerudnik:<br/>vendor/upstream<br/>distro/nix<br/>main"]
  GH -->|"nix.yml build matrix"| CX["Cachix:<br/>jerudnik-jcode.cachix.org<br/>(prebuilt x86_64/aarch64-linux,<br/>aarch64-darwin)"]
  GH -->|"scripts/sync-local.sh"| L["local clone<br/>~/infrastructure/jcode"]
  GH -->|"nix flake update jcode"| FX["4nix consumer<br/>jcode.url = github:jerudnik/jcode/main"]
  CX -.->|"substituter<br/>(no local rebuild)"| FX
  CX -.->|"substituter"| L
```

Surfaces and their owners:

| Surface | Updated by | Authoritative? |
|---|---|---|
| `upstream/master` | upstream maintainers | source of truth for upstream code |
| `github/{vendor,distro/nix,main}` | `Fork maintenance` CI every 6h | yes (only writer) |
| Cachix `jerudnik-jcode` | `nix.yml` build matrix on push | prebuilt artifact cache |
| local clone | `scripts/sync-local.sh` | read-only mirror of GitHub |
| 4nix `jcode` input | `nix flake update jcode` in `~/infrastructure/4nix` | consumer pin |

The Cachix cache is what keeps real-time local resource use low: 4nix and local
`nix build` pull prebuilt binaries from `jerudnik-jcode.cachix.org` (trusted in
`4nix/modules/defaults.nix`) instead of recompiling the Rust workspace.

## Updating the 4nix consumer pin

4nix consumes `jcode.url = "github:jerudnik/jcode/main"`. Its `flake.lock` pins a
specific `main` rev and only moves when you bump it:

```sh
cd ~/infrastructure/4nix
nix flake update jcode          # repin jcode/main to the latest reconciled tip
nix flake check                 # or the repo's preflight/validation gate
git commit -m "chore(flake): bump jcode" flake.lock
```

Prefer bumping after the GitHub `Nix` build matrix is green for that `main` rev,
so the Cachix cache is already populated and the consumer never builds jcode
locally.

